Here's the full **testsmells.org 19-smell academic catalog** audit of `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, with integration-test calibration applied.

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 3           | 3              |
| Medium   | 1           | 1              |
| Low      | 0           | 0              |
| **Total**| **4**       | **4** (of 8)   |

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH — Smell 3: Sleepy Test

**Test:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(3000); // ← blocks for 3 seconds unconditionally
```

**Why it's bad:** `Thread.Sleep` introduces non-deterministic timing. On a slow CI agent 3 s may not be enough; on a fast machine it wastes time. Even in integration tests, sleep-based waits are a smell (per calibration: downgrade for resource use, but *not* for sleeps).

**Fix:** Replace with a polling/retry loop or async event:
```csharp
// Option A: poll with timeout
var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
while (sw.Elapsed < TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
{
    if (_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id)) break;
    await Task.Delay(100);
}
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));

// Option B (preferred): expose an awaitable from the repository
await _repository.WaitForNotificationAsync(user.Id, timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky failures in CI; suite slowdown scales linearly with test count.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Smell 1: Conditional Test Logic

**Test:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101-108)

```csharp
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

**Why it's bad:** One branch always runs and the other is *never* exercised, creating a hidden testing gap. If the production code changes the return type, the test silently switches branches instead of failing.

**Fix:** Split into two deterministic tests:
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenStandard_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<User>(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_WhenPremium_HasPositiveDiscount()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", discountRate: 0.1m));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<PremiumUser>(loaded);
    Assert.IsTrue(((PremiumUser)loaded).DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False pass — you're only testing one type path and don't know which.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Smell 4: Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)

**Test:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 113-119)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }
    // ← no assertion — passes even if every insert silently fails
}
```

**Why it's bad:** MSTest reports this as "passed" as long as no exception is thrown. If `Insert` starts silently swallowing errors, this test gives false confidence.

**Fix:** Assert the outcome:
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRecords()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False confidence — zero defect-detection capability.

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM — Extended Smell: Assertion Roulette

**Test:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35-39)

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
// ← 4 assertions, zero descriptive messages
```

**Why it's bad (per Peruma et al., 2020):** When one fails, the CI log says `Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<Alice>. Actual:<null>` with no context about *which property* was wrong or *why* it matters. With 4 assertions and no messages, diagnosing failures requires reading the source.

**Fix:** Add message parameters:
```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip through persistence");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip through persistence");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Database should assign a positive auto-increment ID");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slower failure diagnosis, especially in CI logs.

---

## Smells Scanned & Found Clean (15 of 19)

| Smell | Status | Notes |
|-------|--------|-------|
| Mystery Guest | ✅ Clean | In-memory SQLite (`Data Source=:memory:`) — no external resources |
| Eager Test | ✅ Clean | No test calls 4+ distinct production methods |
| Magic Number Test | ✅ Clean | `3` and `10` in count assertions are self-documenting (items just added) |
| Sensitive Equality | ✅ Clean | No `ToString()` in assertions |
| Exception Handling | ✅ Clean | No `try`/`catch` in test methods |
| General Fixture | ✅ Clean | Both `_connection` and `_repository` are used by all 8 tests |
| Ignored/Disabled Test | ✅ Clean | No skipped tests |
| Duplicate Assert | ✅ Clean | No repeated identical assertions |
| Lazy Test | ✅ Clean | Each test has a distinct primary action |
| Constructor Init | ✅ Clean | Properly uses `[TestInitialize]`, not a constructor |
| Default Test | ✅ Clean | Class name is descriptive |
| Redundant Print | ✅ Clean | No debug output statements |
| Redundant Assertion | ✅ Clean | No tautological assertions |
| Resource Optimism | ✅ Clean | In-memory database, no assumed external files |
| Empty Test | ✅ Clean | No empty test bodies |

---

## Well-Written Tests Worth Highlighting

- **`DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase`** — Clean arrange-act-assert, single clear assertion, descriptive name.
- **`InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity`** — Good concurrency test with a meaningful assertion. LINQ-based setup is clear, not conditional logic.
- **`UpdateUser_ModifiesExistingRecord`** — Focused, good lifecycle coverage.

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Test | Effort | Action |
|----------|-------|------|--------|--------|
| 1 | Assertion-Free Test | `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` | 2 min | Add `Assert.AreEqual(100, ...)` |
| 2 | Conditional Test Logic | `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` | 10 min | Split into two deterministic tests |
| 3 | Sleepy Test | `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` | 15 min | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with poll/await |
| 4 | Assertion Roulette | `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | 3 min | Add message strings to all 4 assertions |

**Bottom line:** 4 of 8 tests are clean and well-structured. The 4 smelly tests have straightforward fixes — the assertion-free test (#1) is the highest-risk item since it has zero defect-detection capability today.
